{"cursor":"25858","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n{{Infobox scientist\n| birth_name = Esther Miriam Zimmer image = Esther Lab.jpg image_size = caption\n| = Stanford University laboratory birth_date = birth_place = Bronx, New York\n| death_date = death_place = residence = citizenship = nationality = ethnicity =\n| field = Microbiology Microbial Genetics work_institution = Stanford\n| University University of Wisconsin alma_mater = Hunter College Stanford\n| University University of Wisconsin doctoral_advisor = R. Hans Brink\n| doctoral_students = known_for = Lambda phage, specialized transduction,\n| replica plating, fertility factor F, Plasmid Reference Center\n| author_abbreviation_bot = author_abbreviation_zoo = honors = Pasteur Award,\n| Dernham Postdoctoral Fellowship in Oncology, President of the Stanford Chapter\n| of Sigma Xi religion = footnotes =\n}} 'Esther Miriam Zimmer Lederberg' (December 18, 1922 – November 11,\n2006) was an American microbiologist and a pioneer of bacterial genetics.\nNotable contributions include the discovery of the bacterial virus Î», the\ntransfer of genes between bacteria by specialized transduction, the development\nof replica plating, and the discovery of the bacterial fertility factor F.\n\nLederberg also founded and directed the now defunct Plasmid Reference Center\nat Stanford University, where she maintained, named, and distributed\nplasmids of many types, including those coding for antibiotic resistance,\nheavy metal resistance, virulence, conjugation, colicins, transposons, and\nother unknown factors.\n","linknr":296,"url":"Esther_Lederberg","recorded":1364157975,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Esther_Lederberg&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Esther_Lederberg&action=edit","//en.wikipedia.org/apple-touch-icon.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentC